Import and export data

1 Data import

Datasets contained in R packages are great for learning. However, at some point, we will be interested in analyzing our own data. In this section we will learn how to read different file formats into R.

1.1 Formats

Data is often collected in the spreadsheet file format (.xlsx) used by Excel. However, in data processing environments, simple text files with values separated by characters (commas, semicolons, tabs, spaces) are preferred. In the end, the aim is always to save a data record in a format that is as simple as possible and therefore also saves memory space and is not prone to errors.

In R, delimited text file formats are preferred for import and export because the process is fast and error-free.

1.1.1 Delimited Text File Formats

In this section, youll learn how to import data in the delimited text file format. For this type of formats, we will use the readr package, which is part of the core tidyverse. First, install the package and load the library.

install.packages("tidyverse",
                 repos = "http://cran.us.r-project.org") # install package
library(tidyverse)                                       # load

The package readr includes several functions convenient to read each type of delimited text file:

1.1.1.1 read_csv()

read_csv() reads comma delimited files. The first argument to read_csv() is the most important: it is the path to the file to read.

If you specify your working directory (wd) before importing the file, you will only need to tell read_csv() the name of the file to read.

So, first, set your working directory to the place where you have your input and want your output.

setwd("path/to") # set wd

Then, read the australia.csv file with the function read_csv and assign the file to an object called australia_csv to be saved in the R environment.

australia_csv <- read_csv(file = "australia.csv") # read and save
head(australia_csv, # show me how it looks
     n = 3)         # only 2 rows

If the file was in other directory different to our set working directory, we should have included the path before the file name.

# read .csv file and save it in an object
australia_csv <- read_csv(file = "other/path/to/australia.csv") 
# show me the first 2 rows
head(australia_csv,
     n = 2)

Of course, if you only need to import this one file, it doesnt make much difference which of the two latter ways of import to use. However, when you import and export many files, it is quickly worthwhile using the first way, because the working directory only has to be specified once, so that all following paths can be shortened.

Notice that in the top right part of R studio a new data variable has turned up. This variable references the loaded data. Via this variable you can access the data set and execute various R functions on the data set, like calculating the mean value of a certain column, etc.

Notice also that there are some missing values within the data, some of them are represented as "-", other by ".". We can tell read_csv() what characters should be consider as missing values with the argument na. The function identifies those characters as missing values and convert them into NA.

australia_csv <- read_csv(file = "australia.csv", 
                          na = c("-",".")) # identify missing values
head(australia_csv,
     n = 3)                                # show me how it looks

By default, read_csv() uses the first row as column names. If the data does not have column names, you can use col_names = FALSE to tell read_csv() not to treat the first row as column names, and instead label them sequentially from X1 to Xn:

australia_csv <- read_csv(file = "australia.csv",
                          na = c("-","."),
                          col_names = FALSE )  # there is no header 
head(australia_csv, 
     n = 2)

Alternatively you can pass col_names a character vector which will be used as the column names:

australia_csv <- read_csv(file = "australia.csv",
                          na = c("-","."),
                          col_names = c("ENV","LOC","YEAR","GEN","YIELD","HEIGHT","LODGING","SIZE","PROTEIN","OIL")) # there are no headers, introduce column names.
head (australia_csv, 
      n = 2)

You can specify the type of each column with the col_types argument. I may want the column loc to be a factor with levels a not a character. We can specify the type of columns in a compact format as: c(ffffdddddd). f stands for factor and d for double (numeric variable with decimals). Other options are: c = character, l = logical, D = date, T = date time, t = time.

australia_csv <- read_csv(file = "australia.csv", 
                          na = c("-","."),
                          col_types = c("ffffdddddd")) # specify column type
head(australia_csv, # show me how it looks
     n = 2)

readr functions all have similar syntax: once you have mastered one, you can use the others with ease.

1.1.1.2 read_csv2()

read_csv2() reads semicolon separated files (common in countries where , is used as the decimal place).

australia_csv2 <- read_csv2(file = "australia_semicolon.csv") 
head(australia_csv2,  # show me how it looks
     n = 2)

1.1.1.3 read_tsv()

read_tsv() reads tab delimited files.

australia_tsv <- read_tsv(file = "australia_tabs.txt") 
head(australia_tsv, # show me how it looks
     n = 2)

1.1.1.4 read_delim()

read_delim() reads in files with any delimiter. We only need to specify the delimiter that separates our data with delimargument.

# read file delimited by blank spaces
australia_spaces <- read_delim(file = "australia_spaces.txt", 
                               delim = " ") # space blank delimiter
head(australia_spaces,
     n = 2)
# read file delimited by tabs
australia_tabs <- read_delim(file = "australia_tabs.txt", 
                             delim = "\t")  # tab separated
head(australia_tabs,
     n = 2)
# read file delimited by commas
australia_csv <- read_delim(file = "australia.csv", 
                            delim = ",")   # comma separated
head(australia_csv,
     n = 2)

1.1.2 Excel (.xlsx) files

Since many people record their data with Excel or have them in Excel, functions to import data directly from this format have been developed. readxl package enables importing specific sheets. You can even use the argument range to select only a part of a spreadsheet.

First, install and load the package.

install.packages("readxl", 
                 repos = "http://cran.us.r-project.org") # install package
library(readxl)

Use read_xlsx() to read the australia.xlsx file, the first sheet called Subset1 and specify the range you would like to read, in this case, only the matrix of cells from A1 to B3.

read_xlsx(path = "australia.xlsx", # file to read
          sheet = "Subset1",       # sheet to read
          range = "A1:B3")         # range to read

1.2 Import by clicking

One of the advantages of R studio is that some of these processes can be made by clicking. Lets read some of the previous files without coding.

Go to the environment pane and click on Import Dataset, choose the type of file and open it! Simple, isnt it?

2 Export

Similar to the import functions shown above, there are also specific functions for exporting data.

2.1 Delimited Text File Formats

The readr package also includes functions convenient to write each type of delimited text file:

2.1.1 write_csv()

write_csv() writes comma delimited files.

Again, if you have already specified your working directory, the file will be saved within it. If you have not specified it yet or you want to save it somewhere else, specify the whole path in the path argument.

I will save the data set mtcars in a csv file. I need to specify the table that I want to save and the path where I want to save it. Note that we have created a new folder within our wd called Output, where we want our files to be saved. We specify in the path argument the new folder and the name of the file, i.e."Output/mtcars.csv".

head(mtcars,                            # data frame we want to save
     n = 2)                            
write_csv(x = mtcars,                   # data set to save
          path = "Output/mtcars.csv")   # directory and filename

We can specify if the data set has column names or not, or how we want our Nas to be coded.

write_csv(x = mtcars,                   # data set to save
          path = "Output/mtcars.csv",   # directory and filename (.csv)
          na = "NA",                    # code missing values as "NA"
          col_names = FALSE)            # the data set does not have headers

2.1.2 write_csv2()

write_csv2() writes semicolon delimited files.

write_csv2(x = mtcars,                            # data set to save
          path = "Output/mtcars_semicolon.csv")   # directory and filename(.csv)

2.1.3 write_tsv()

write_tsv() writes tab delimited files.

write_tsv(x = mtcars,                        # data set to save
          path = "Output/mtcars_tabs.txt")   # directory and filename (.txt)

2.1.4 write_delim()

write_delim() writes files with any delimiter. We only need to specify the delimiter that separates our data with delim argument.

# write file delimited by blank spaces
write_delim(x = mtcars,                        # data set to save
            path = "Output/mtcars_spaces.txt", # directory and filename (.txt)
            delim = " ")                       # space blank delimiter


# write file delimited by tabs
write_delim(x = mtcars,                        # data set to save
            path = "Output/mtcars_tabs.txt",   # directory and filename (.txt)
            delim = "\t")                      # tab delimiter

# write file delimited by commas
write_delim(x = mtcars,                        # data set to save
            path = "Output/mtcars_csv.csv",    # directory and filename (.csv)
            delim = ",")                       # comma delimiter

2.2 Excel (.xlsx) files

It is also possible to export directly to Excel files. For this, openxlsx package is great.

install.packages("openxlsx",
                 repos = "http://cran.us.r-project.org") # install package
library(openxlsx)                                        # load package

The simple export of a table into a file works with write.xlsx() analogous to the other functions:

write.xlsx(x=mtcars,                    # data set to save
           file="Output/mtcars.xlsx",   # path and filename
           sheetName="mtcars_sheet1")   # sheet name

But the most interesting feature about this package is that allows you writing several tables in different sheets of one file. First, you need to create a workbook. Then, add as many sheets as you want. After, write one table for each sheet. Finally, save the workbook.

myworkbook <- createWorkbook()                            # create the workbook

addWorksheet(wb = myworkbook,                             # add 1st sheet in wb
             sheetName = "Sheet1")                        # Name of the sheet

addWorksheet(wb = myworkbook,                             # add 2nd sheet in wb
             sheetName = "Sheet2")                        # Name of the sheet

writeData(wb = myworkbook,                                # write table in wb
          sheet = "Sheet1",                               # specify sheet
          x = mtcars)                                     # specify data table
  
writeData(wb = myworkbook,                                # write table in wb
          sheet = "Sheet2",                               # specify sheet
          x = iris)                                       # specify data table

saveWorkbook(myworkbook,                                  # Save workbook
             file="Output/myworkbook.xlsx",               # Path and filename
             overwrite = TRUE)                            # Overwrite each time

3 Other alternatives

Sometimes the data that we want to work with is not on our computer but on the web. The same readr functions can be apply for reading URLs. We only need to specify the path and use the right function depending on the format file.

# data (import via URL)

dat <- read_csv(file = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/SchmidtPaul/DSFAIR/master/data/Mead1993.csv")
head (dat, 
      n = 2)

Other option is to paste data directly from the clipboard. Assuming we have data in the Windows clipboard (for example, copied data from Excel), to put that data into a variable named copiedata we use:

copiedata <- read.delim("clipboard")
head(copiedata)

Well, now you have the knowledge needed to start working with your own data. Keep this cheatsheet close so you can check it out any time you need it.
